<color=13><i>The following section requires MS Access and knowledge of SQL (Structured Query Language). There are plenty of websites that offer a quick and easy tutorials on the language, which is not to difficult to learn. What's used extensively is the "WHERE" clause of the query statements which retrieves the data you want. Note that it also case-sensitive and spelling sensitive :). To help out, you can take a look at the database tables as examples to refer to.
</i>
<b><u>Adding a new OCC</u></b>
<b>1.</b> After opening up the database, click the OCC table
<b>2.</b> Under the column "OCC", type in a name for the OCC
<b>3.</b> Using the SQL statement "ID IN", type in the OCC skills, under "OCC Skills" column, using the id index for the skill. For example, if you want to include the skill, Cryptography that has an id index of 88, type in "ID IN (88)". You can also include more if desired, like "ID IN (77, 88, 54, 100, ...)"
<b>4.</b> Then include the "Other skills" under the "Other" column field using the "WHERE" clause of the SQL query. Ex. <i>Category='Physical' OR (Category='WP' AND ID NOT IN (62, 22)) OR ID IN (99).</i>
<b>5.</b> Afterwards, indicate how many skills the user is allowed to select when he or she chooses their "Other" skills. To do this type in the number under the "NumOther" column.
<b>6.</b> <i>(Optional)</i> If you're OCC requires the user to select MOS skills or select Secondary skills (like in Macross II) do the following. Under the MOS column check to indicate that the OCC requires MOS selection or under the NumSecondary column type in the limit.
<b>7.</b> Players will notice that OCC skills and some Other skills get a bonus. Each bonus is separated with an appersand, '&' and uses either the format of <i>[skill id] : [bonus score] </i> or a SQL statement (<i>Category='Physical' OR (Category='WP' AND ID NOT IN (62, 22)) OR ID IN (99)</i>) followed by a colon and the score ie. <i>[sql statement] : [bonus score]</i>.
<b>8. </b>Type in the SDC of the OCC under the "SDC" column

<b><u>Adding a new skill</u></b>
<b>1.</b> After opening up the database, click the Skills table.
<b>2.</b> Under the column "Skill", type in the name of the skill
<b>3.</b>Under the "Category" column, type in the name of the category, like "Physical" or "Communication" or "Special" if the skill is exclusive to an OCC.
<b>4.</b> Under the "Base" and "Experience" column, type in the base score of the skill and the amount of experience per level, respectively.
<b>5.</b> (<i>Optional</i>) If the score doesn't require a base score, like a weapon proficiency skill, physical skill or a skill that needs to notify the user of any extra notes, you can enter extra data. To do this, click the Extra table and type in the corresponding skill id and type in the extra info under the "ID" and "Info" column.

<b><u>Adding a new race</u></b>
<i>Ex. Martian- IQ: 7d6 + 88 + 1d6, PS: 1d6 +1 +2d6 ........</i>
<b>1.</b> To better explain this section, we'll use the above example. Click the Race table.
<b>2.</b> Under the race column, type in the name of the race such as "Martian"
<b>3.</b> Each attribute is broken down to three columns, for example IQ has "IQx", "IQ+", and "IQx+".  "IQx" refers to the intial role. In the Martian example it is 7d6. Type in "7" under this column to represent 7d6. This lets the program know that the intial roll requires 7 random rolls of d6s. "IQ+" refers to any additional number to be added after the intial roll. In the Maritian example it is 88. Type in "88" or whatever number you desire. "IQx+" refers to additional rolls of d6s. In the Maritian example, it is 1d6. So type in "1" or any other number including zero. Likewise for "IQ+", if the race does not require additional points, type in "0".
<b>4.</b> Continue with the other attributes.

</color>
